{"pageProps":{"note":{"id":"AjAwbCGQG0EQnKwLHQkjF","title":"Lecture 9","desc":"","updated":1637898856515,"created":1635140067611,"custom":{},"fname":"courses.Semester 5.Embedded Systems.Lecture 9","type":"note","vault":{"fsPath":"vault"},"contentHash":"9343b2e8d68a716bf9a7351e4f3be126","links":[],"anchors":{"keyboard-cont-switches-relays-and-opto-isolators":{"type":"header","text":"Keyboard (Cont.), Switches, Relays and Opto-Isolators","value":"keyboard-cont-switches-relays-and-opto-isolators","line":8,"column":0,"depth":1},"points":{"type":"header","text":"Points","value":"points","line":10,"column":0,"depth":2},"c-program-to-read-keypad-and-send-result-to-portd":{"type":"header","text":"C program to read keypad and send result to PORTD","value":"c-program-to-read-keypad-and-send-result-to-portd","line":13,"column":0,"depth":2},"extra-points":{"type":"header","text":"Extra Points","value":"extra-points","line":28,"column":0,"depth":2},"relays":{"type":"header","text":"Relays","value":"relays","line":43,"column":0,"depth":2},"opto-isolators":{"type":"header","text":"Opto-Isolators","value":"opto-isolators","line":58,"column":0,"depth":2}},"children":[],"parent":"a1PatlsCiz7PYsL111lFm","data":{}},"body":"<h1 id=\"lecture-9\"><a aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"anchor-heading\" href=\"#lecture-9\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\"><use xlink:href=\"#svg-link\"></use></svg></a>Lecture 9</h1>\n<h1 id=\"keyboard-cont-switches-relays-and-opto-isolators\"><a aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"anchor-heading\" href=\"#keyboard-cont-switches-relays-and-opto-isolators\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\"><use xlink:href=\"#svg-link\"></use></svg></a>Keyboard (Cont.), Switches, Relays and Opto-Isolators</h1>\n<h2 id=\"points\"><a aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"anchor-heading\" href=\"#points\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\"><use xlink:href=\"#svg-link\"></use></svg></a>Points</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><img src=\"/notes/assets/images/2021-10-25-11-39-22.png\"></li>\n</ul>\n<h2 id=\"c-program-to-read-keypad-and-send-result-to-portd\"><a aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"anchor-heading\" href=\"#c-program-to-read-keypad-and-send-result-to-portd\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\"><use xlink:href=\"#svg-link\"></use></svg></a>C program to read keypad and send result to PORTD</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>Note that here Columns are connected in PC0 - PC3 and rows are connected to PC4 - PC7.</li>\n<li><img src=\"/notes/assets/images/2021-11-26-09-02-21.png\">\n<ul>\n<li>The above code maintains all the initialization work.</li>\n<li>Sets KEY_PRT and other variables to the required values.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><img src=\"/notes/assets/images/2021-11-26-09-03-22.png\">\n<ul>\n<li>This part of the code checks whether initially keyboard is pressed then allow everything to complete.</li>\n<li>Then ground all the rows and read the columns</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><img src=\"/notes/assets/images/2021-11-26-09-05-23.png\">\n<ul>\n<li>If key is pressed, check which one is pressed.</li>\n<li>Thus, one by one we ground the rows and check the value of column.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><img src=\"/notes/assets/images/2021-11-26-09-07-36.png\">\n<ul>\n<li>Finally, use the lookup array created in the first image and use it to identify which key was pressed.</li>\n<li>Then, send it to PORTD for output.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<h2 id=\"extra-points\"><a aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"anchor-heading\" href=\"#extra-points\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\"><use xlink:href=\"#svg-link\"></use></svg></a>Extra Points</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><img src=\"/notes/assets/images/2021-11-26-09-16-37.png\"></li>\n<li><img src=\"/notes/assets/images/2021-11-26-09-16-46.png\"></li>\n<li>BJT (Bi-polar Junction Transistor) as a switch\n<ul>\n<li><img src=\"/notes/assets/images/2021-11-26-09-17-35.png\"></li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>Transistors\n<ul>\n<li>We can switch devices using transistors</li>\n<li>It amplifies the signals</li>\n<li>Circuit Diagram\n<ul>\n<li><img src=\"/notes/assets/images/2021-11-26-09-18-34.png\"></li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>Darlington Transistors\n<ul>\n<li><img src=\"/notes/assets/images/2021-11-26-09-19-10.png\"></li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>MOSFET as a switch\n<ul>\n<li><img src=\"/notes/assets/images/2021-11-26-09-20-04.png\"></li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<h2 id=\"relays\"><a aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"anchor-heading\" href=\"#relays\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\"><use xlink:href=\"#svg-link\"></use></svg></a>Relays</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><img src=\"/notes/assets/images/2021-11-26-09-20-40.png\"></li>\n<li>Components\n<ul>\n<li>Coil</li>\n<li>Spring</li>\n<li>Contacts</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>Relay Diagrams\n<ul>\n<li><img src=\"/notes/assets/images/2021-11-26-09-21-38.png\"></li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>Limitations of electromechanical relays\n<ul>\n<li>Low life expectancy</li>\n<li>High wear and tear</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>Advantages of Sold State Relays\n<ul>\n<li>High life expectancy</li>\n<li>Low wear and tear</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<h2 id=\"opto-isolators\"><a aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"anchor-heading\" href=\"#opto-isolators\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\"><use xlink:href=\"#svg-link\"></use></svg></a>Opto-Isolators</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><img src=\"/notes/assets/images/2021-11-26-09-24-53.png\"></li>\n<li>Components\n<ul>\n<li>LED</li>\n<li>Photo-Transistor</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>Controlling a lamp via optoisolator\n<ul>\n<li><img src=\"/notes/assets/images/2021-11-26-09-27-14.png\"></li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>","noteIndex":{"id":"GL4YoVrbDUHLnf946YtXV","title":"Curated Notes","desc":"","updated":1630150480330,"created":1629975412335,"custom":{"nav_order":0,"permalink":"/"},"fname":"root","type":"note","vault":{"fsPath":"vault"},"contentHash":"59326d3738fbbdf94df0792937dea389","links":[],"anchors":{},"children":["3ONxZ3Khb7nFPdLxlV1ib","Jq5ki9jf1QLTdc3DYLRW4","t5S98zYhQcXKMjbqBsVGg","Z2JlSyF7TPv3hFanVQhJd"],"parent":null,"data":{},"body":"\n\n\nYou have